{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-js","path":"/the-resting-potential","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>Communication across neurons happens by the means of electric-signals. The electricity is due to the presence of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi><msup><mi>a</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">+</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Na^{+}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.771331em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">a</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.771331em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">+</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>K</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">+</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K^{+}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.771331em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.771331em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">+</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><msup><mi>a</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Ca^{2+}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">a</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">+</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><msup><mi>l</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">−</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Cl^{-}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.771331em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.01968em;\">l</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.771331em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">−</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> ions. These <em>charges</em> are present around the neurons, separated by a neuron's membrane. This separation creates a <em>potential difference</em>. If a neuron is at rest this <em>potential difference</em> is then called the <em>resting potential</em>.</p>\n<h3 id=\"facts\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#facts\" aria-label=\"facts permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Facts</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>Charges that cause neural activity: <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>N</mi><msup><mi>a</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">+</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Na^{+}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.771331em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">N</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">a</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.771331em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">+</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>K</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">+</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K^{+}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.771331em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.771331em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">+</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><msup><mi>a</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Ca^{2+}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">a</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">+</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><msup><mi>l</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">−</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Cl^{-}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.771331em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.01968em;\">l</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.771331em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">−</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> ions.</li>\n<li>The <em>potential difference</em> of a neuron at rest is called <em>resting potential</em>.</li>\n<li><em>Membrane potential</em> is the voltage across the membrane of a neuron. (values lie between <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>90</mn><mtext>mV</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">-90\\text{mV}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.76666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mord\">9</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">mV</span></span></span></span></span> <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>60</mn><mtext>mV</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">+60\\text{mV}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.76666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">+</span><span class=\"mord\">6</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">mV</span></span></span></span></span>).</li>\n<li><em>Resting potential</em> is the <em>membrane potential</em> of a neuron at rest. The values are about <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>70</mn><mtext>mV</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">-70\\text{mV}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.76666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mord\">7</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">mV</span></span></span></span></span>.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>If the outside of a neuron at rest is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>50</mn><mtext>mV</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">50\\text{mV}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">5</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">mV</span></span></span></span></span> more positive than it's inside, then the <em>membrane potential</em> is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>50</mn><mrow><mi>m</mi><mi>V</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">-50{mV}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.76666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mord\">5</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">m</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">V</span></span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<h2 id=\"ionic-movement\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#ionic-movement\" aria-label=\"ionic movement permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Ionic movement</h2>\n<p>So far we have established that neurons have electric charges due to the presence of some ions. We also went through membrane potential and some values that they may have. Let's try to visualize how the charges are acquired.</p>\n<h3 id=\"diffusion\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#diffusion\" aria-label=\"diffusion permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Diffusion</h3>\n<p>Imagine a liquid in a container. Adding a drop of colour will cause the colour to disperse farther from the point of initial contact in a random fashion. Diffusion defines movement from a region of high concentration to lower concentration. This means at some point the concentration throughout the liquid will be similar at that point the movement would cease.</p>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 690px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blog/static/f23329315eadb13edc978c0d904df7db/274e1/diffusion.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 75.14450867052024%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Fig: Diffusion of K+ ions, movement from a region of high-concentration (inside the membrane) to low-concentration (outside the membrane).\"\n        title=\"Fig: Diffusion of K+ ions, movement from a region of high-concentration (inside the membrane) to low-concentration (outside the membrane).\"\n        src=\"/blog/static/f23329315eadb13edc978c0d904df7db/15ec7/diffusion.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/blog/static/f23329315eadb13edc978c0d904df7db/9ac50/diffusion.jpg 173w,\n/blog/static/f23329315eadb13edc978c0d904df7db/8d48c/diffusion.jpg 345w,\n/blog/static/f23329315eadb13edc978c0d904df7db/15ec7/diffusion.jpg 690w,\n/blog/static/f23329315eadb13edc978c0d904df7db/af659/diffusion.jpg 1035w,\n/blog/static/f23329315eadb13edc978c0d904df7db/89b2d/diffusion.jpg 1380w,\n/blog/static/f23329315eadb13edc978c0d904df7db/274e1/diffusion.jpg 2160w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 690px) 100vw, 690px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Fig: Diffusion of K+ ions, movement from a region of high-concentration (inside the membrane) to low-concentration (outside the membrane).</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<h3 id=\"electrostatic-forces\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#electrostatic-forces\" aria-label=\"electrostatic forces permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Electrostatic forces</h3>\n<p>Charges can be positive or negative depending on the presence of electrons in the material. If same type of charges are brought together, they will repel each other. Charged materials seek the opposite type of charge to balance their excess or deficit of charge so that they can go back to their non-ionized, natural state.\n<figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 690px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blog/static/d8fed2073a117883539455c09457b6be/274e1/electrostatics-and-k-plus-ions.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 75.14450867052024%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Fig: Electrostatic effects prevent movement across the ion channel\"\n        title=\"Fig: Electrostatic effects prevent movement across the ion channel\"\n        src=\"/blog/static/d8fed2073a117883539455c09457b6be/15ec7/electrostatics-and-k-plus-ions.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/blog/static/d8fed2073a117883539455c09457b6be/9ac50/electrostatics-and-k-plus-ions.jpg 173w,\n/blog/static/d8fed2073a117883539455c09457b6be/8d48c/electrostatics-and-k-plus-ions.jpg 345w,\n/blog/static/d8fed2073a117883539455c09457b6be/15ec7/electrostatics-and-k-plus-ions.jpg 690w,\n/blog/static/d8fed2073a117883539455c09457b6be/af659/electrostatics-and-k-plus-ions.jpg 1035w,\n/blog/static/d8fed2073a117883539455c09457b6be/89b2d/electrostatics-and-k-plus-ions.jpg 1380w,\n/blog/static/d8fed2073a117883539455c09457b6be/274e1/electrostatics-and-k-plus-ions.jpg 2160w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 690px) 100vw, 690px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Fig: Electrostatic effects prevent movement across the ion channel</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<h2 id=\"building-charges\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#building-charges\" aria-label=\"building charges permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Building charges</h2>\n<p>Let's assume a scenario, if the concentration of say, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>K</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">+</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K^{+}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.771331em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.771331em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">+</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> ions inside the neuron is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>200</mn><mi>m</mi><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">200 mM</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">m</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span> while outside the concentration is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>10</mn><mi>m</mi><mi>M</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">10mM</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\">m</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">M</span></span></span></span>, then diffusion will cause <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>K</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">+</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K^{+}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.771331em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.771331em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">+</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> ions to move outside. This follows a more positive charge on the outside of the neuron's membrane. The movement is facilitated by ion channels, these ion channels have limited permeability which is different for different ions. </p>\n<p>As the positive charge grows, it becomes harder for other ions to move out. (Refer to the comic in <a href=\"#electrostatic-forces\">Electrostatic Forces</a>), you can now imagine the two forces taking part in a tug of war. In terms of statistics, only 1 in 100,000 <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>K</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">+</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">K^{+}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.771331em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.771331em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">+</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> ions need to move out to reach equilibrium of these forces. This shows how much dominant is the electrostatic force over the force of diffusion.</p>\n<p>It is worth taking a note that the volume of ions on either side of the membrane don't drive the electrical potential of the neuron. The important bit is the concentration gradient. We can understand more from the <strong>Nernst Equation</strong>. <strong>Nernst Equation</strong> describes the electric potential, given the concentration of ions around the membrane. </p>\n<h2 id=\"nernst-equation\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#nernst-equation\" aria-label=\"nernst equation permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Nernst Equation</h2>\n<span class=\"katex-display\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>R</mi><mi>T</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>z</mi><mi>F</mi></mrow></mfrac><mi>ln</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mfrac><mtext>ion concentration outside </mtext><mtext>ion concentration inside</mtext></mfrac></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">E = \\frac{RT}{zF}\\ln{\\frac{\\text{ion } \\text{concentration } \\text{outside }}{\\text{ion } \\text{concentration } \\text{inside}}}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">E</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:2.05744em;vertical-align:-0.686em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mopen nulldelimiter\"></span><span class=\"mfrac\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.36033em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.314em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.04398em;\">z</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.23em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"frac-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.677em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"mord mathdefault\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.686em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose nulldelimiter\"></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\">ln</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mopen nulldelimiter\"></span><span class=\"mfrac\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.37144em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.314em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">ion </span></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">concentration </span></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">inside</span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.23em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"frac-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.677em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">ion </span></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">concentration </span></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">outside </span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.686em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose nulldelimiter\"></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>","timeToRead":3,"excerpt":"Communication across neurons happens by the means of electric-signals. The electricity is due to the presence of , ,  and  ions. These…","frontmatter":{"title":"The Resting potential","cover":"https://picsum.photos/seed/seed_n/1500/300","date":"2020-04-23T00:00:00.000Z","cate